# ACME over Cloudflare DNS-01 — rename to `tls-cloudflare.conf` to activate.
# ===========================================================================
# WHEN YOU NEED THIS
#
# With the orange cloud ON, Cloudflare terminates TLS at its edge. That breaks
# the TLS-ALPN-01 challenge outright (the challenge never reaches your origin),
# and it makes HTTP-01 fragile — "Always Use HTTPS" and some Bot Fight
# behaviour can intercept /.well-known/acme-challenge/ before it gets to you.
# DNS-01 sidesteps both: Caddy proves control of the name by writing a TXT
# record, so nothing depends on inbound traffic reaching the origin at all.
#
# REQUIRES
#   * the custom Caddy build (Dockerfile.caddy bundles caddy-dns/cloudflare);
#     stock caddy:2 fails with "unrecognized directive: dns"
#   * CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN in .env
#
# THE TOKEN
# Create it at Cloudflare → My Profile → API Tokens → Create Token → custom:
#     Permissions:    Zone / DNS / Edit
#     Zone Resources: Include / Specific zone / <your zone only>
# Do NOT use a Global API Key. A Global Key is your whole account; this token
# can edit DNS in one zone and nothing else. Rotate it if it ever leaks — see
# runbook.md.
# ===========================================================================

tls {
	dns cloudflare {env.CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN}

	# Ask a public resolver directly for the challenge TXT record. Without
	# this, propagation checks go through the container's resolver, which on
	# some hosts is a caching resolver that keeps serving NXDOMAIN long enough
	# for the validation to time out.
	resolvers 1.1.1.1 8.8.8.8
}

# ── Optional: Cloudflare Authenticated Origin Pulls (mTLS) ─────────────────
# Makes the origin refuse any TLS connection that does not present
# Cloudflare's client certificate, so an attacker who learns your origin IP
# cannot bypass Cloudflare by connecting to it directly. Free on all plans.
#
# Setup:
#   1. Cloudflare → SSL/TLS → Origin Server → Authenticated Origin Pulls: on
#   2. Download Cloudflare's origin-pull CA certificate
#   3. Mount it into the caddy container and point `client_auth` at it
#
# VERIFY THE SYNTAX AGAINST YOUR CADDY VERSION before enabling: the
# `client_auth` sub-directive was renamed between Caddy 2.7 and 2.8
# (`trusted_ca_cert_file` became `trust_pool file`). `caddy validate` will
# tell you which one your build wants. Getting this wrong means Caddy refuses
# to start, which on a live host means an outage.
#
# tls {
# 	client_auth {
# 		mode require_and_verify
# 		trusted_ca_cert_file /etc/caddy/cloudflare-origin-pull-ca.pem
# 	}
# }
#
# Note you cannot have two `tls` blocks in one site. Merge the `client_auth`
# block into the `tls` block above rather than adding a second one.
